<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Grounds two branding decisions under the execution epic
  <a href="/backlog/2256-constellation-branding-and-website-design/">#2256</a>, both amendments to the
  prepared branding-system decision
  <a href="/backlog/2209-ratify-the-constellation-branding-system-naming-marks-icon-r/">#2209</a>:
  <a href="/backlog/2249-decide-the-system-wide-visual-language-flat-vs-rich-dimensi/">#2249</a>
  (the system-wide visual language &mdash; flat-minimal vs rich-dimensional) and
  <a href="/backlog/2250-we-mark-system-multi-color-umbrella-vs-monochrome/">#2250</a>
  (the Web&nbsp;Everything mark system &mdash; multi-color umbrella vs strict monochrome). The full
  survey and source list are in the session report
  (<code>reports/2026-07-04-constellation-visual-language-and-color-architecture.md</code>); the visual
  candidates render at <code>plateau:branding.html#journeys</code> and in
  <code>plateau:branding-proposals/loop/</code>.
</p>

<h2>Axis A &mdash; flat-minimal vs rich-dimensional</h2>
<p>
  The industry pendulum swung from iOS&nbsp;7 flat (2013) through the neumorphism accessibility failure
  (~2020) back to depth in 2025 &mdash; Apple <strong>Liquid Glass</strong> (WWDC 2025, iOS&nbsp;26)
  and Google <strong>Material&nbsp;3 Expressive</strong> &mdash; but a 2025&ndash;26 usability backlash
  (NN/g measured contrast as low as 1.5:1; iOS&nbsp;26.1 added a Clear/Tinted toggle) settled the
  consensus on <em>skeuomorphic minimalism</em>: selective <em>soft</em> depth, not full skeuomorphism.
</p>
<p>
  For a team-of-one hand-authoring SVG whose highest-frequency surface is a 16px favicon, the decisive
  constraints all point one way: small-size guidance rules out gradient-as-depth and glass (they muddy on
  downscale); a convincing SVG glass effect (stacked <code>feGaussianBlur</code> /
  <code>feDisplacementMap</code> / <code>feSpecularLighting</code>) exceeds the hand-authoring craft
  ceiling; a flat mark recolors trivially across light and dark at near-zero weight; and both depth
  revivals showed depth-encoded meaning failing WCAG contrast even at Apple/Google scale. Leaders put
  depth in UI chrome and marketing while keeping the <em>core mark flat</em>, at most conceding a
  gradient or dual-tone (Stripe, Figma, Instagram) &mdash; never inner-shadow or glass.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Recommendation:</strong> default flat-minimal for the marks &mdash; grounded on brand-character
  fit (a standards layer reads <em>principled / bedrock / timeless</em>, where glossy depth reads as
  consumer-product flashiness), with the 16px-physics and craft-ceiling arguments demoted to a
  <em>size-gated</em> rule both branches must honour. Restrained depth (the
  <code>plateau:branding-proposals/loop/plateau-rich-a.svg</code> probe &mdash; radial glow highlight + a
  soft <code>feDropShadow</code> + an edge-highlight stroke, not full 3D) is permitted only on
  large-rendered surfaces (&ge;128px) via a script-decidable floor; glass / full-3D is banned at every
  size.
</p>

<h2>Axis B &mdash; multi-color umbrella vs strict monochrome</h2>
<p>
  Master-brand vs sub-brand color architecture divides on a real fault line.
  <strong>JetBrains</strong> (a smooth multi-stop umbrella <em>gradient</em> square spanning the family
  palette, over per-product 2-color squares) and <strong>NBCUniversal</strong>'s "collective
  contributions of the corporate family" peacock are precedents for <em>the parent spans the family
  palette; each child a subset</em>. But JetBrains' umbrella is a <em>gradient</em>, not overlapping
  color regions &mdash; so the precedent authorizes a palette-spanning gradient, which the "one gradient"
  rule <em>already permits</em>, not a Venn. <strong>Adobe</strong> (monochrome red parent, colored
  per-product tiles) and Google Cloud / Material product icons run the <em>inverse</em> &mdash; restrained
  parent, color pushed down to products for wayfinding.
</p>
<p>
  The "union of colors = we contain everything" trope is legitimate as <em>meaning</em> but its default
  <em>form</em> &mdash; overlapping translucent circles &mdash; is a worn cliche that fails the
  ownability test ("would this work just as well for another company? &mdash; Mastercard owns overlapping
  circles; everyone else looks like a subsidiary"). Our own WE Venn probes
  (<code>we-venn-lumin.svg</code>, <code>weB-venn-constellation.svg</code>) are built with
  <code>mix-blend-mode:screen</code> over translucent radial circles &mdash; exactly the muddy-blend,
  floating-Venn construction the prior art flags &mdash; and a tri-hue union legible at 16px collides
  with #2209 Fork 2's ratified mono-W favicon.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Recommendation:</strong> deliver the "everything unified" meaning <em>within</em> the
  one-gradient rule, via a <strong>constellation-spanning multi-stop gradient</strong>
  (indigo&rarr;cyan&rarr;violet) &mdash; a 3-stop gradient is still "one gradient," matches JetBrains'
  actual umbrella construction, downscales cleanly at 16px, and stays compatible with #2209 Fork 2. The
  overlapping-color-region Venn is banned; strict monochrome is the lower-risk fallback. The final-mark
  execution is <a href="/backlog/2256-constellation-branding-and-website-design/">#2251</a>'s job.
</p>

